1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,880
 Hi, this is Maria from dresspattingmaking.com.

2
00:00:07,880 --> 00:00:13,640
 This is part 5 in the pants block series, and I'll be drafting the pants block for Anne.

3
00:00:13,640 --> 00:00:16,880
 I'm firstly comparing Anne's figure to the standard figure.

4
00:00:16,880 --> 00:00:20,360
 Anne has less difference between her waist and hips than any of the figures I've done

5
00:00:20,360 --> 00:00:21,360
 so far.

6
00:00:21,360 --> 00:00:24,780
 The standard figure has 10 inches difference between the waist and hips.

7
00:00:24,780 --> 00:00:29,040
 Mine has more Jane had less, but Anne has even less.

8
00:00:29,040 --> 00:00:32,520
 The difference between Anne's waist and hip is 6.25 inches.

9
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:37,680
 Now Anne's thigh is actually just slightly bigger than the standard figure.

10
00:00:37,680 --> 00:00:41,960
 By which I mean, most pant block making instructions don't require the thigh measurement.

11
00:00:41,960 --> 00:00:43,720
 You don't need it to draft the block.

12
00:00:43,720 --> 00:00:47,360
 It's an assumed measurement, which works out as a percentage of the hip.

13
00:00:47,360 --> 00:00:51,560
 So the standard figure, as far as most western sewing patterns are concerned, have a thigh

14
00:00:51,560 --> 00:00:54,920
 measurement that is 60% of the hip measurement.

15
00:00:54,920 --> 00:00:58,880
 Given that Anne's thigh to hip proportion is very similar to the standard figure, that

16
00:00:58,880 --> 00:01:03,840
 is 60.2% of her hip measurement, you might then assume she'd end up with a good result

17
00:01:03,840 --> 00:01:09,360
 for her thigh using those instructions where the thigh is worked out as 60% of the hip.

18
00:01:09,360 --> 00:01:13,640
 However, the other part of those block making instructions that creates a difficulty for

19
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:19,480
 Anne is that they say to use the widest measurement below your waist as your hip measurement.

20
00:01:19,480 --> 00:01:24,400
 So for Anne, her thigh would be worked out based on her high hip and it would end up

21
00:01:24,400 --> 00:01:25,400
 being too big for her.

22
00:01:25,400 --> 00:01:29,720
 Now, the whole purpose of these comparisons that I'm doing to the standard figure and

23
00:01:29,720 --> 00:01:34,040
 standard pants instructions was to show that these particular figure types that I'm drafting

24
00:01:34,040 --> 00:01:40,760
 pants for if they use those standard instructions would not end up with a good initial result.

25
00:01:40,760 --> 00:01:45,000
 The other problems for Anne would have been her back and front crotch lengths.

26
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:50,040
 On the left is what Anne's block would look like if drafted using that system compared

27
00:01:50,040 --> 00:01:55,100
 to what her blocks look like on the right, taking into account her actual thigh measurement,

28
00:01:55,100 --> 00:01:59,560
 not using her upper hip as the width of her block and checking she has the crotch length

29
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:02,080
 she needs front and back.

30
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:06,360
 And this is the same two blocks but this time superimposed so you can more clearly see the

31
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:08,320
 difference between them.

32
00:02:08,320 --> 00:02:12,600
 So I'm going to start drafting Anne's block from this point here, the instructions up

33
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:17,720
 to this point were the same for everybody and that's all covered in video too.

34
00:02:17,720 --> 00:02:23,120
 I'm going to zoom in to 200% of the previous image while working on the foundation.

35
00:02:23,120 --> 00:02:27,040
 The first thing I'll do is lower the crotch, currently the crotch depth is the body crotch

36
00:02:27,040 --> 00:02:29,680
 depth and we'll need some ease.

37
00:02:29,680 --> 00:02:35,120
 From point D I will measure down 5/8 of an inch at right angles to the C to D line and

38
00:02:35,120 --> 00:02:37,400
 mark point D1.

39
00:02:37,400 --> 00:02:42,520
 I will continue the L to I line down below the body crotch depth line for about an inch

40
00:02:42,520 --> 00:02:45,600
 or so, that's shown by the pink arrow.

41
00:02:45,600 --> 00:02:51,160
 Then draw a line at right angles to touch point D1, that's shown by the blue arrow.

42
00:02:51,160 --> 00:02:53,680
 This will help later for drawing the crotch curve.

43
00:02:53,680 --> 00:02:59,320
 The horizontal line touching D1 is the depth of the crotch plus ease.

44
00:02:59,320 --> 00:03:03,360
 Wear those two lines intersect I've marked point X.

45
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:06,160
 So now I'll do the calculation for the waist shaping.

46
00:03:06,160 --> 00:03:12,400
 I'll take Anne's waist measurement which is 39 and 3/4 inches and add 1 inch for ease.

47
00:03:12,400 --> 00:03:18,400
 I'll then take that total 40 and 3/4 inches and divide it by 4.

48
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:23,600
 So the waist measurement for the front and back will be 10 1/8 of an inch.

49
00:03:23,600 --> 00:03:27,800
 With the other figures I started the waist shaping by coming in 1/2 an inch from point

50
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:31,400
 L on the waist and marking point P.

51
00:03:31,400 --> 00:03:37,040
 Then drawing a straight line from P to low hip point J, this line would be the center

52
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:38,040
 front line.

53
00:03:38,040 --> 00:03:41,720
 However, I'm not going to do that with am.

54
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:45,280
 I want to go back and look at the waist shaping for the other three figures.

55
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:47,280
 Here's the waist shaping for the standard figure.

56
00:03:47,280 --> 00:03:50,920
 The pink shaded areas are basically dark values.

57
00:03:50,920 --> 00:03:55,560
 They are not actually darts as in a folded piece of fabric, but those areas are acting

58
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:56,800
 as darts.

59
00:03:56,800 --> 00:04:01,120
 That shaping, those dart equivalents go right down to the low hip.

60
00:04:01,120 --> 00:04:05,120
 My waist shaping also goes down to the low hip and because I have a proportionally smaller

61
00:04:05,120 --> 00:04:11,080
 high hip, I have more shaping or more taken out at the high hip level than the standard

62
00:04:11,080 --> 00:04:13,000
 figure did.

63
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:17,680
 Notice that with Jane, on her side seam the shaping only goes down to her high hip.

64
00:04:17,680 --> 00:04:19,800
 It doesn't go all the way down to the low hip.

65
00:04:19,800 --> 00:04:23,600
 At the center front she does have some shaping down to her low hip.

66
00:04:23,600 --> 00:04:27,480
 Here with them all together you can see that most of the shaping is done at the side seam

67
00:04:27,480 --> 00:04:28,880
 and at the center front.

68
00:04:28,880 --> 00:04:34,720
 They all have only one dart in the center and a very similar size, despite the differences

69
00:04:34,720 --> 00:04:36,880
 in the waist and the hip.

70
00:04:36,880 --> 00:04:41,720
 Now Jane's larger circumference is at her high hip, therefore we want the shaping to

71
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:45,760
 stop there at the high hip and not go down to the low hip.

72
00:04:45,760 --> 00:04:49,920
 If we followed the directions for the standard waist shaping and drew a line from P down

73
00:04:49,920 --> 00:04:54,480
 to the low hip, we would be cutting some off at the high hip, which is why we don't want

74
00:04:54,480 --> 00:04:57,840
 to follow those directions for shaping the waist for Anne.

75
00:04:57,840 --> 00:05:01,480
 Therefore, I'm not going to do any shaping at the center front.

76
00:05:01,480 --> 00:05:06,520
 I will draw a straight line from point L at the waist down to point J at the low hip.

77
00:05:06,520 --> 00:05:08,920
 This will be the center front line.

78
00:05:08,920 --> 00:05:13,600
 Now the issue is we do want a straight line from the waist to the low hip so we can put

79
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:14,600
 a zip in it.

80
00:05:14,600 --> 00:05:18,320
 We don't really want a curved line there, we certainly can't go from the waist to the

81
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:22,520
 high hip in a straight line and then down from there, that wouldn't work.

82
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:25,600
 So I'm not going to do any shaping for Anne at the center front.

83
00:05:25,600 --> 00:05:30,080
 Doing the waist shaping at the side seam and with darts will limit that shaping down to

84
00:05:30,080 --> 00:05:31,640
 her high hip.

85
00:05:31,640 --> 00:05:36,880
 So using the result of the calculation I did earlier, I'll take 10 1/8 of an inch and

86
00:05:36,880 --> 00:05:39,040
 add 1/2 an inch for a dart.

87
00:05:39,040 --> 00:05:46,000
 From point L at the waist, I'll measure towards 0.0 at the side seam for 10 5/8 of an inch

88
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,640
 and mark point P.

89
00:05:48,640 --> 00:05:54,200
 So moving on to the high hip, I'll take the high hip measurement of 46 7/16 of an inch

90
00:05:54,200 --> 00:06:00,160
 and add 1 inch ease, divide that total by 4 and I get 11 7/8 of an inch.

91
00:06:00,160 --> 00:06:06,240
 I'll measure on the high hip line from point K towards the side seam point N and mark point

92
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:07,240
 Q.

93
00:06:07,240 --> 00:06:11,880
 As you'll notice, I actually have to go beyond point N to mark point Q, that's not a problem,

94
00:06:11,880 --> 00:06:17,360
 I was expecting that because I drafted the width of the foundation to her low hip measurement.

95
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:23,080
 She is larger at her high hip, therefore this will extend out beyond point N.

96
00:06:23,080 --> 00:06:24,080
 Now I'll draw the dart in.

97
00:06:24,080 --> 00:06:29,760
 I've allowed for 1/2 an inch dart, I'll center it on point A and make it 3 inches long.

98
00:06:29,760 --> 00:06:34,040
 Now I've actually taken an extra measurement for Anne between her waist and her high hip

99
00:06:34,040 --> 00:06:35,780
 to help with the shaping.

100
00:06:35,780 --> 00:06:39,440
 I've taken that measurement 1 1/2 inches below the waist.

101
00:06:39,440 --> 00:06:44,800
 So doing the usual calculation, adding 1 inch ease and dividing by 4, I get an amount

102
00:06:44,800 --> 00:06:48,080
 of 10 inches and 11/16.

103
00:06:48,080 --> 00:06:54,120
 I'll measure across from point R towards the side seam and mark point S. However note

104
00:06:54,120 --> 00:06:58,680
 that this crosses the dart and that dart amount should not be included as it will be

105
00:06:58,680 --> 00:07:01,480
 closed when the dart is sewn.

106
00:07:01,480 --> 00:07:06,960
 Therefore, I need to actually measure to the dart, stop measuring, start measuring from

107
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:10,760
 the other side of it and then mark point S.

108
00:07:10,760 --> 00:07:16,240
 Now if I try and draw a side seam using the current side seam points from P at the waist

109
00:07:16,240 --> 00:07:19,520
 to see at the hip, I do not get a good result at all.

110
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:22,880
 I can't make that into a good side seam curve.

111
00:07:22,880 --> 00:07:27,480
 Now it would work if I could ignore point M but we don't really want to do that and

112
00:07:27,480 --> 00:07:30,760
 there's some other things we can do to get better shape.

113
00:07:30,760 --> 00:07:35,920
 What I'm actually going to do is try and draw a side seam curve concentrating on the curve

114
00:07:35,920 --> 00:07:41,160
 from the high hip down to the low hip and thigh and then trying to get that curve to

115
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:43,160
 go up to the waist.

116
00:07:43,160 --> 00:07:48,320
 Now I'm not going to worry about trying to hit point S that extra measurement because

117
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:51,280
 that point will change when I put a second dart in.

118
00:07:51,280 --> 00:07:56,600
 I'll have to measure around that second dart at that depth like I did the first dart.

119
00:07:56,600 --> 00:08:01,320
 So I'm actually drawing in a curve first and then working out the dart from that curve.

120
00:08:01,320 --> 00:08:02,720
 You could do it the other way.

121
00:08:02,720 --> 00:08:09,280
 There might be some twinging and throwing trying to get the right dart width but that's part

122
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:11,000
 of the process.

123
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:16,640
 So if I'm working with that curve as my side seam then point P to P2 will be the value

124
00:08:16,640 --> 00:08:21,720
 of my second dart otherwise that would be extra ease at the waist which we don't want.

125
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:24,800
 Note that this side seam curve is still a bit of a guess at the moment.

126
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:29,120
 I'll mark in that second dart and check I have enough room on the low waistline that

127
00:08:29,120 --> 00:08:33,840
 is from point R to S. It might not be right, I might have to go back and try another dart

128
00:08:33,840 --> 00:08:37,480
 width etc but this is what I'm trying first.

129
00:08:37,480 --> 00:08:40,840
 This is just an aside, it's not following on from the previous slide.

130
00:08:40,840 --> 00:08:46,000
 This is just an example of another side seam I could try, that blue arrow that's the side

131
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 seam.

132
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:51,720
 If I did use this one I would have a bigger dart at the waist because point P to point O

133
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:54,600
 is wider than point P to P2 was.

134
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:57,280
 There is no problem with the waist being the width of the block.

135
00:08:57,280 --> 00:09:01,000
 It would just mean that there is no waist shaping at the side seam and no waist shaping

136
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:02,300
 at the center front.

137
00:09:02,300 --> 00:09:05,080
 All of the shaping would be done by the two darts.

138
00:09:05,080 --> 00:09:09,000
 Given Ann's figure, there's no problem with all of the shaping being done by the darts

139
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:14,320
 and no shaping being done at the center front or at the side seam.

140
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:18,560
 So back to the previous side seam curve that I drew.

141
00:09:18,560 --> 00:09:22,320
 From P to P2 is 9/16 of an inch.

142
00:09:22,320 --> 00:09:27,120
 Now if this was actually much larger, if I was using the value that I showed you on the

143
00:09:27,120 --> 00:09:32,920
 previous slide, I would probably add the two dart values together and then divide by two

144
00:09:32,920 --> 00:09:39,120
 and change the other dart, but 9/16 of an inch is almost half an inch.

145
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:44,360
 So I will just make this dart 9/16 of an inch wide.

146
00:09:44,360 --> 00:09:51,480
 So I've drawn a dart 9/16 of an inch wide at about 1 1/2 inches from the first dart.

147
00:09:51,480 --> 00:09:53,640
 That is of course towards the side seam.

148
00:09:53,640 --> 00:10:00,000
 I've then re-measured from point, art point S and not included those dart values, re-plotted

149
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:01,520
 point S.

150
00:10:01,520 --> 00:10:05,800
 Now there is a little bit of extra ease there between point S and the side seam, but I'm

151
00:10:05,800 --> 00:10:07,520
 just going to go with this.

152
00:10:07,520 --> 00:10:10,400
 If this was your block, you could try and finesse it further.

153
00:10:10,400 --> 00:10:15,480
 Alternatively, you could just shape the darts differently rather than make that dart leg

154
00:10:15,480 --> 00:10:19,840
 straight, they could go out a bit wider at the bottom so that you could take that extra

155
00:10:19,840 --> 00:10:21,760
 ease in.

156
00:10:21,760 --> 00:10:23,560
 So this is where I'm up to now with the block.

157
00:10:23,560 --> 00:10:26,320
 I have the side seam and I have the two darts.

158
00:10:26,320 --> 00:10:30,880
 What's left is the crotch curve in getting the extra crotch length that's needed, later

159
00:10:30,880 --> 00:10:34,240
 on of course finishing off the leg shaping.

160
00:10:34,240 --> 00:10:39,840
 Now I'm going to draw in the crotch curve from point J on the low hip down to point D1,

161
00:10:39,840 --> 00:10:42,280
 which is the crotch depth plus some ease.

162
00:10:42,280 --> 00:10:48,080
 I'll draw an arrow one inch long from point X and that one inch line is shown by the pink

163
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:49,080
 arrow.

164
00:10:49,080 --> 00:10:54,080
 I'll draw 45 degrees to the horizontal and vertical guidelines that the X is constructed

165
00:10:54,080 --> 00:10:55,080
 on.

166
00:10:55,080 --> 00:10:57,640
 I'll then use a French curve to draw the curve.

167
00:10:57,640 --> 00:11:01,840
 Note that if you watch my last video, this one inch guide that helps me draw the curve

168
00:11:01,840 --> 00:11:08,200
 works because Anne's thigh is almost the same proportion to her low hip as the standard

169
00:11:08,200 --> 00:11:09,920
 figure.

170
00:11:09,920 --> 00:11:13,560
 For other figures, depending on their hip thigh proportion, the length of that arrow

171
00:11:13,560 --> 00:11:15,520
 will be a bit more or less.

172
00:11:15,520 --> 00:11:21,800
 That's covered in video four, it's around nine and a half minutes or so.

173
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:26,040
 For Anne, that one inch length arrow, which is the same as the standard figure, works

174
00:11:26,040 --> 00:11:30,680
 to get a good curve and that's because, as I said, Anne's low hip to thigh proportion

175
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:33,200
 is very similar to the standard figure.

176
00:11:33,200 --> 00:11:37,600
 So her extension is the same proportion to her hip.

177
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:40,680
 Now that I've drawn the curve, I can measure the front crotch length.

178
00:11:40,680 --> 00:11:43,960
 When I measure it, I will not measure right up to point L at the waistline.

179
00:11:43,960 --> 00:11:50,680
 I will stop about 3/16 or 1/4 of an inch before point L and I'll call that point L2.

180
00:11:50,680 --> 00:11:55,040
 I will measure from point L2 to point D1.

181
00:11:55,040 --> 00:11:58,000
 Note that the waistline is completely straight.

182
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:03,220
 When we join those two pieces together, when we sew them at the center front line, that

183
00:12:03,220 --> 00:12:05,920
 waistline is still straight.

184
00:12:05,920 --> 00:12:09,600
 In the last slide, you may have thought, well, obviously.

185
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:14,680
 But in this slide, notice that the waist is completely straight, but when the two fronts

186
00:12:14,680 --> 00:12:17,480
 are sewn together, there is a curve.

187
00:12:17,480 --> 00:12:21,400
 And that's because this block had some shaping done at the center front.

188
00:12:21,400 --> 00:12:24,920
 So the center front line is on an angle.

189
00:12:24,920 --> 00:12:30,360
 So with Anne's center front being completely vertical, with no waist shaping angle, if

190
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:35,400
 we want a gentle curve on the waist, we need to cut a little bit off the top so we get

191
00:12:35,400 --> 00:12:41,000
 this curve instead of a completely straight waist.

192
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:45,600
 Just a note, and I may well have missed pointing this out before, when I measure from point

193
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:50,360
 L2 to point D1, I'm not actually measuring the front crotch length.

194
00:12:50,360 --> 00:12:54,080
 I'm measuring the front crotch length plus some ease.

195
00:12:54,080 --> 00:12:58,720
 So the pink line is a little bit longer than the body measurement.

196
00:12:58,720 --> 00:13:02,960
 So it's best to add about 3/8 of an inch to the body measurement to get the crotch length

197
00:13:02,960 --> 00:13:08,080
 you need, otherwise it will be a little tight or very fitting.

198
00:13:08,080 --> 00:13:13,640
 In my previous videos, in order to get extra length, in those videos, it was the pat back.

199
00:13:13,640 --> 00:13:16,040
 I used the cut and spread method.

200
00:13:16,040 --> 00:13:21,000
 That meant cutting the paper that you're drafting on and putting paper underneath, spreading

201
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:24,040
 the required amount and sticking it down with sticky tape.

202
00:13:24,040 --> 00:13:28,760
 Now I'll be doing a similar thing to get the same result, but in a different way, so not

203
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:31,720
 actually cutting the paper.

204
00:13:31,720 --> 00:13:36,680
 This time I'm going to put a piece of cardboard or paper underneath the paper I'm drafting

205
00:13:36,680 --> 00:13:37,680
 on.

206
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:41,800
 Now cardboard is better because it's easier to trace around, but paper's fine too.

207
00:13:41,800 --> 00:13:45,560
 Obviously, in real life, you wouldn't be able to see the paper underneath, but I'm showing

208
00:13:45,560 --> 00:13:51,880
 it to you with a yellowish square that I have paper underneath the foundation.

209
00:13:51,880 --> 00:13:56,280
 Using either a tracing wheel to trace, either just by itself, one of those tracing wheels

210
00:13:56,280 --> 00:14:02,480
 that leaves little puncture marks or with tracing paper that leaves colored dots.

211
00:14:02,480 --> 00:14:05,840
 You can use the tracing wheel or an all to mark key points.

212
00:14:05,840 --> 00:14:11,260
 When you later pull that piece of paper out, you join up those dots that you've made with

213
00:14:11,260 --> 00:14:16,680
 a ruler and a pencil or a French curve and a pencil.

214
00:14:16,680 --> 00:14:21,120
 So I'm showing you in green what I want imprinted onto the cardboard below.

215
00:14:21,120 --> 00:14:25,360
 I want the outline in green and the lines in green.

216
00:14:25,360 --> 00:14:29,660
 So definitely I need to mark the low hip, the high hip, the low waist.

217
00:14:29,660 --> 00:14:33,960
 Need to mark the darts, the dart points, not the legs on the waistline.

218
00:14:33,960 --> 00:14:38,280
 So the green shape and the green lines are what is being marked through from the paper

219
00:14:38,280 --> 00:14:41,320
 to the cardboard or paper underneath.

220
00:14:41,320 --> 00:14:46,600
 What I don't want to mark, what I want to exclude is the front crotch curve.

221
00:14:46,600 --> 00:14:50,520
 So when I pull the cardboard out, I use a pencil and draw those lines in.

222
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:54,240
 If you use a tracing wheel and colored tracing paper, then you don't need to draw the lines

223
00:14:54,240 --> 00:14:55,240
 in.

224
00:14:55,240 --> 00:14:56,240
 They're already there.

225
00:14:56,240 --> 00:15:00,240
 And then you cut this shape out and be very accurate in the cutting.

226
00:15:00,240 --> 00:15:01,240
 So here it is cut out.

227
00:15:01,240 --> 00:15:05,800
 I'll make sure it's correct by placing it on top of my draft and checking it.

228
00:15:05,800 --> 00:15:12,880
 So now I will hinge it at point C and pivot it until I have the extra inch length I need.

229
00:15:12,880 --> 00:15:16,680
 The pink arrow is the new front crotch length.

230
00:15:16,680 --> 00:15:20,240
 Now I have worked out, I need one inch extra length.

231
00:15:20,240 --> 00:15:26,240
 But I won't only just open it up one inch where you see that blue wedge.

232
00:15:26,240 --> 00:15:32,040
 I will also then double check and measure that length from D1 up to the waist to make sure

233
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:34,360
 I have the correct length.

234
00:15:34,360 --> 00:15:38,520
 Now just in case anyone looks at this and thinks, well, now we've tilted it.

235
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:41,760
 Did we need to actually stop short of the waist?

236
00:15:41,760 --> 00:15:44,360
 That 3/16 we cut off top of the waist.

237
00:15:44,360 --> 00:15:45,840
 Did we need to do that?

238
00:15:45,840 --> 00:15:49,480
 Since it's now on an angle, does that mean we didn't have to stop short of the waist

239
00:15:49,480 --> 00:15:51,560
 to get that waist curve?

240
00:15:51,560 --> 00:15:52,560
 Well yes we did.

241
00:15:52,560 --> 00:15:54,640
 I'm just showing you here the final block.

242
00:15:54,640 --> 00:15:57,480
 And notice we still only have a gentle curve, very gentle.

243
00:15:57,480 --> 00:16:01,760
 If we had a continued straight up to the waist and not cut that bit off, then we would again

244
00:16:01,760 --> 00:16:04,120
 have a very straight line.

245
00:16:04,120 --> 00:16:07,640
 So now that I have the length I need for the crotch, I will trace around the rest of the

246
00:16:07,640 --> 00:16:10,440
 cutout cardboard.

247
00:16:10,440 --> 00:16:13,840
 And I need to mark all those lines, including the wedge that's been added.

248
00:16:13,840 --> 00:16:16,280
 I need to add the darts, the dart points.

249
00:16:16,280 --> 00:16:20,760
 I will also, when I lift it up, erase the other lines so I don't get confused.

250
00:16:20,760 --> 00:16:25,120
 Now as far as the lines go, you don't need a tracing wheel to get the lower hip, the

251
00:16:25,120 --> 00:16:26,600
 crotch and the high hip.

252
00:16:26,600 --> 00:16:32,760
 You just mark the edges and use a ruler to join up the notches when you lift it up.

253
00:16:32,760 --> 00:16:36,080
 So this is what I have when I've drawn in the lines with the ruler.

254
00:16:36,080 --> 00:16:40,440
 And as I said, erase the lines underneath so they don't confuse me too much.

255
00:16:40,440 --> 00:16:44,800
 Then all we need to do is the leg shaping and the front is finished.

256
00:16:44,800 --> 00:16:52,320
 I'll keep that cardboard, definitely not thrown away, I'll use it again to draft the back.

257
00:16:52,320 --> 00:16:57,640
 So for the final block, I'll also need to extend the grain line up from the crotch level

258
00:16:57,640 --> 00:17:01,240
 because when it got cut, it would have skewed off.

259
00:17:01,240 --> 00:17:05,560
 So extend that straight up to the waistline.

260
00:17:05,560 --> 00:17:09,480
 Make sure you don't rub out the crotch point, that's circled in yellow and the two intersecting

261
00:17:09,480 --> 00:17:14,320
 lines that it's based on, this information should be kept on the block.

262
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:19,360
 That's not obvious from my image, but there should be notches on the edges to mark the

263
00:17:19,360 --> 00:17:24,280
 dark legs and all of those key points, the low hip, the high hip, etc.

264
00:17:24,280 --> 00:17:29,600
 Well, yes, it's a case of do as I say, not as I do.

265
00:17:29,600 --> 00:17:33,960
 The leg shaping needs to be done from the crotch point to the knee with a French curve.

266
00:17:33,960 --> 00:17:36,640
 You may not get at the curve in one pass.

267
00:17:36,640 --> 00:17:41,200
 You may need to draw part of the curve, move the French curve and draw in the second part

268
00:17:41,200 --> 00:17:43,600
 and blend those two lines together.

269
00:17:43,600 --> 00:17:46,560
 And you can always take an extra measurement between the upper thigh and the knee to help

270
00:17:46,560 --> 00:17:47,760
 to do the shaping.

271
00:17:47,760 --> 00:17:53,560
 A good place is the lower thigh, seven and a half or eight inches above the knee.

272
00:17:53,560 --> 00:17:58,480
 So this is Anne's front finished and I'll be starting the back from this point that's

273
00:17:58,480 --> 00:18:01,600
 showing with all the guidelines drawn.

274
00:18:01,600 --> 00:18:07,240
 The plotting of these points is covered in video two from about 18 minutes onwards.

275
00:18:07,240 --> 00:18:10,800
 That applies to all figures, so I'm not going to cover that again.

276
00:18:10,800 --> 00:18:16,240
 Now these next few steps were also covered in video two from about 20 minutes to 23 minutes,

277
00:18:16,240 --> 00:18:18,960
 but I'll cover them again quickly for Anne.

278
00:18:18,960 --> 00:18:23,520
 So I'll draw straight lines from the knee to the ankle, from knee point E to ankle point

279
00:18:23,520 --> 00:18:27,400
 G and from knee point F to ankle point H.

280
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:32,200
 I'll draw a short guideline, about two inches long, down from point C and at right angles

281
00:18:32,200 --> 00:18:33,760
 to the C to D line.

282
00:18:33,760 --> 00:18:38,280
 I'll take Anne's block and turn it upside down and match the inseam knee point of the

283
00:18:38,280 --> 00:18:42,240
 front block with the knee line of the pants back at point E.

284
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:47,240
 I'll rotate the front block until the crotch point touches that guideline I drew in the

285
00:18:47,240 --> 00:18:48,240
 last step.

286
00:18:48,240 --> 00:18:54,120
 I'll name the point where the back crotch touches the guideline point C2 and I'll trace the

287
00:18:54,120 --> 00:18:58,960
 front inner leg curve from the crotch point down to the knee or from the knee up to the

288
00:18:58,960 --> 00:19:00,120
 crotch point.

289
00:19:00,120 --> 00:19:01,120
 Same difference.

290
00:19:01,120 --> 00:19:04,000
 I'll draw the guidelines for the back crotch curve.

291
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:09,320
 I'll extend the L to I line down for a few inches below the crotch level then at right

292
00:19:09,320 --> 00:19:12,840
 angles draw another line to touch point C2.

293
00:19:12,840 --> 00:19:16,080
 I'll mark the intersection of those two lines with an X.

294
00:19:16,080 --> 00:19:20,600
 I'll set aside the pants front for the minute and measuring quarter of an inch from point

295
00:19:20,600 --> 00:19:23,480
 D at mark point D2.

296
00:19:23,480 --> 00:19:27,280
 So I'll bring the front block back again and flip it over to match the out seam point

297
00:19:27,280 --> 00:19:30,200
 of the front with a knee point F of the back.

298
00:19:30,200 --> 00:19:34,640
 I'll rotate the front block until it touches D2.

299
00:19:34,640 --> 00:19:39,320
 I'll trace that front block from point F to point D2.

300
00:19:39,320 --> 00:19:44,080
 So I'm going to use that traced off section of cardboard I used earlier to help to extend

301
00:19:44,080 --> 00:19:47,400
 the front crotch and the first thing I'll do is erase the darts.

302
00:19:47,400 --> 00:19:51,880
 Now I'll be turning this upside down but because I have it translucent I don't want the front

303
00:19:51,880 --> 00:19:53,440
 darts to be confusing things.

304
00:19:53,440 --> 00:19:58,520
 If you're doing this when you turn it upside down you won't see the darts you'll see the

305
00:19:58,520 --> 00:20:02,040
 notches on the edge and you do want to ignore those notches.

306
00:20:02,040 --> 00:20:06,760
 So the front waist darts are not relevant for the back.

307
00:20:06,760 --> 00:20:09,760
 So firstly I flipped it over vertically.

308
00:20:09,760 --> 00:20:14,120
 I still have the waistline on top and the crotch line at the bottom and I'm going to

309
00:20:14,120 --> 00:20:20,080
 measure across from the side seam that is from right to left for the back waist value

310
00:20:20,080 --> 00:20:29,240
 which is ten and one-eighth of an inch plus three-quarters inch dart the total is ten and thirteen-sixteenths.

311
00:20:29,240 --> 00:20:32,160
 So I'll measure from the side seam and mark where the waist ends.

312
00:20:32,160 --> 00:20:36,960
 I'll then draw a line from that point on the waist to the low hip line with a ruler and

313
00:20:36,960 --> 00:20:39,640
 pencil then cut that bit off.

314
00:20:39,640 --> 00:20:43,860
 I have to say here that I find the imperial system extremely painful.

315
00:20:43,860 --> 00:20:47,520
 Is America ever going to get on the same page as every other country and move to the decimal

316
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:48,520
 system?

317
00:20:48,520 --> 00:20:50,320
 That's my winge.

318
00:20:50,320 --> 00:20:55,360
 So I'm going to draw a line starting at point X and at 45 degrees to the two guidelines where

319
00:20:55,360 --> 00:21:01,520
 X is the intersection and that line indicated by the arrow is two inches long that's going

320
00:21:01,520 --> 00:21:05,600
 to help draw a curve from point C to the tip of that arrow.

321
00:21:05,600 --> 00:21:10,520
 Now this might seem odd but firstly I'm going to draw a curve just from point C2 to the

322
00:21:10,520 --> 00:21:13,160
 tip of the arrow with the help of the French curve.

323
00:21:13,160 --> 00:21:17,480
 We haven't got the other points yet for the rest of the back curve but I am starting with

324
00:21:17,480 --> 00:21:22,160
 just that little bit of the back curve from point C to the arrow tip.

325
00:21:22,160 --> 00:21:26,480
 Ants back crotch length is 17 inches and 15/16ths.

326
00:21:26,480 --> 00:21:30,840
 So I've measured that little curve that I've drawn from C2 to the arrow tip and it's four

327
00:21:30,840 --> 00:21:32,920
 and 3/8ths of an inch.

328
00:21:32,920 --> 00:21:36,680
 Now I'm going to measure from the waist to the crotch depth on the cardboard that I'm

329
00:21:36,680 --> 00:21:37,680
 using.

330
00:21:37,680 --> 00:21:41,960
 Now this should be the crotch depth from the front but it is minus that little bit that

331
00:21:41,960 --> 00:21:44,840
 was taken off at the center front waist.

332
00:21:44,840 --> 00:21:48,400
 So rather than going and finding the crotch depth measurement on the table and remembering

333
00:21:48,400 --> 00:21:52,840
 how much we came down just measure the cardboard.

334
00:21:52,840 --> 00:21:56,960
 So I have to work out how much to tilt the foundation shape of the cardboard up to get

335
00:21:56,960 --> 00:21:58,680
 the length that I need.

336
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:04,200
 Ants back crotch length is 17 and 15/16ths minus what we have which is the curve measurement

337
00:22:04,200 --> 00:22:06,400
 and the cardboard measurement.

338
00:22:06,400 --> 00:22:11,400
 So I'm short about four and one-eighths of an inch that's how much needs to be inserted.

339
00:22:11,400 --> 00:22:17,120
 So I'll tilt that cardboard up to get that length and then I'll draw a curve with a

340
00:22:17,120 --> 00:22:24,480
 French curve of course making sure that from C to up to the waist is 17 and 15/16ths of

341
00:22:24,480 --> 00:22:26,000
 an inch.

342
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:30,440
 So after checking that back crotch length is correct I will lastly trace around that

343
00:22:30,440 --> 00:22:34,520
 cardboard shape to get my final foundation shape for the back.

344
00:22:34,520 --> 00:22:39,960
 Now I'll make sure that I transfer all the lines and make markings to the paper underneath.

345
00:22:39,960 --> 00:22:46,160
 So the low hip line, the high hip etc and actually I haven't drawn the dart in, we'll

346
00:22:46,160 --> 00:22:48,040
 have to do it that at some point.

347
00:22:48,040 --> 00:22:53,720
 So a bit of finessing of the side seam will be needed and also this will need to be true

348
00:22:53,720 --> 00:22:55,200
 to the front.

349
00:22:55,200 --> 00:22:59,960
 The shape of the side seam doesn't have to be identical to the front just the same length.

350
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:01,760
 So I've got to put in the back dart.

351
00:23:01,760 --> 00:23:06,080
 Midway on the waist I'll put in the dart at right angles to the waistline.

352
00:23:06,080 --> 00:23:13,200
 I've allowed for 3/4 inch wide dart and it's about 4 1/2 inches long.

353
00:23:13,200 --> 00:23:15,560
 So here it is finished, back and front.

354
00:23:15,560 --> 00:23:19,880
 As I said it needs to be true, they need to be true to each other, crotch curve in seam,

355
00:23:19,880 --> 00:23:21,840
 out seam, waistline etc.

356
00:23:21,840 --> 00:23:25,560
 I've covered that in previous videos, I won't go through that again.

357
00:23:25,560 --> 00:23:30,800
 I've got the grain line, I've marked the block, I haven't shown notches but yes they would

358
00:23:30,800 --> 00:23:31,800
 all need to be notched.

359
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:36,060
 All of those key points need to be notched, the darts need to have little holes put through

360
00:23:36,060 --> 00:23:40,960
 them so you can put your pencil through to mark the paper underneath.

361
00:23:40,960 --> 00:23:43,480
 So that's it, that's Anne's block finished.

362
00:23:43,480 --> 00:23:49,640
 My next videos are going to be pattern making bust cups and then why upper bust?

363
00:23:49,640 --> 00:23:55,480
 This is Maria from Dress Pappen Making, ciao.

